<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-168-180  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 168 180.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 3 1989 n242 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cable fails; satellite steps in.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Preston, Robert; Schultz, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Both European spurs of TAT-8, the first-ever digitaltrans-Atlantic cable, broke down forcing a shift of system trafficto satellite.andP;  International satellites take a fraction of asecond to transmit a voice 22,000 miles up and down the earth, adelay which disrupts telephone conversations.andP;  Adversely affectedby the shift were customers whose applications work only on cable,particularly those that depend on high-speed data transmission,TAT-8 began operations in late 1988.andP;  The recent breakdown was thesecond and third the system suffered since its installation.andO;TAT-8 is jointly owned by ATandamp;T, France Telecom, British TelecomInternational Inc and 27 other partners.andP;  The outage lasted fourdays.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsFiber OpticsCablesInternational CommunicationsCommunications EquipmentTAT-8 (Telecommunication system).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>